"Friborg T., Soegaard H., Christensen T.R., Lloyd C.R., Panikov N.S.","Siberian wetlands: Where a sink is a source",2003,"Geophysical Research Letters","30","21",,"CLM 5","1 - CLM 5-4",,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-1642316430&partnerID=40&md5=1c306e41bbcfa0796db430c37c8f5e08","Institute of Geography, Univ. of Copenhagen, Oester Voldgade 10, Copenhagen 1350K, Denmark; Dept. Phys. Geogr./Ecosyst. Analysis, GeoBiosphere Science Centre, Lund Univ., Lund SE-2210, Sweden; CEH Wallingford, Maclean Building Crowmash Gifford, Wallingford, Oxfordshire OX10 8BB, United Kingdom; Department of Chemistry/Chem. Biol., Stevens Institute of Technology, Hoboken, NJ 07030, United States","Friborg, T., Institute of Geography, Univ. of Copenhagen, Oester Voldgade 10, Copenhagen 1350K, Denmark; Soegaard, H., Institute of Geography, Univ. of Copenhagen, Oester Voldgade 10, Copenhagen 1350K, Denmark; Christensen, T.R., Dept. Phys. Geogr./Ecosyst. Analysis, GeoBiosphere Science Centre, Lund Univ., Lund SE-2210, Sweden; Lloyd, C.R., CEH Wallingford, Maclean Building Crowmash Gifford, Wallingford, Oxfordshire OX10 8BB, United Kingdom; Panikov, N.S., Department of Chemistry/Chem. Biol., Stevens Institute of Technology, Hoboken, NJ 07030, United States","A greenhouse gas inventory can for some ecosystems be based solely on the net CO2 exchange with the atmosphere and the export of dissolved organic carbon. In contrast, the global warming effect may be more complex in ecosystems where other greenhouse gases such as CH4 or N2O have significant exchanges with the atmosphere. Through micrometeorological landscape-scale measurements from the largest wetlands on Earth in West Siberia we show that CH4 has a stronger effect than CO2 on the greenhouse gas budget in terms of radiative forcing on the atmosphere. Direct measurements of the CO2 and CH4 exchange during the summer of 1999 show that these wetland ecosystems, on average, acted as net sinks of carbon of 0.5 g C m-2 day-1 but large net sources of CH4. Given the high Global Warming Potential of CH4, the Siberian wetlands are an important source of radiative forcing, even in comparison to anthropogenic emissions. Copyright 2003 by the American Geophysical Union.",,"Carbon dioxide; Ecosystems; Global warming; Greenhouse effect; Wetlands; Anthropogenic emissions; Greenhouse gases; Geophysics; biogeochemical cycle; carbon dioxide; methane; source-sink dynamics; wetland; Eurasia; Siberia",,,,,,"Aubinet, M., Estimates of annual net carbon and water exchange of forests: The EUROFLUX methodology (2000) Adv. Ecol. Res., 30, pp. 113-175; Baldocchi, D.D., Fluxnet: A tool to study the temporal and spatial variability of ecosystem-scale carbon dioxide, water vapor, and energy densities (2001) Bull. Am. Meteorol. Soc., 82, pp. 2415-2434; Christensen, T.R., Keller, M., Element interactions and trace gas exchange (2003) Element Interactions: Rapid Assessment Project of SCOPE, , edited by J. M. Melillo, C. B. Field, and B. Moldan, Island Press, Washington, DC; Table HI (2001) World Carbon Dioxide Emissions from the Consumption and Flaring of Fossil Fuels, 1990-1999, , http://www.cia.doe.gov/emeu/iea/tableh1.html, Energy Information Administration (EIA), EIA, Washington, DC (Available as); Friborg, T., Christensen, T.R., Soegaard, H., Rapid response of greenhouse gas emission to early spring thaw in a subarctic mire as shown by micro-meteorological techniques (1997) Geophys. Res. Lett., 24, pp. 3061-3066; Houghton, J.T., Ding, Y., Griggs, D.J., Noguer, M., van den Linden, P.J., Dai, X., Maskell, K., Johnson, C.A., (2001) Climate Change 2001: The Scientific Basis. Contribution of Working Group 1 to the Third Assessment Report of the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change, p. 881. , (Eds.), Cambridge Univ. Press, New York; Matthews, E., Fung, I., Methane emission from natural wetlands: Global distribution, area, and environmental characteristics of sources (1987) Global Biogeochem. Cycles, 1, pp. 61-86; Moncrieff, J.B., Massheder, J.M., DeBruin, H., Elbers, J., Friborg, T., Huesunkveld, B., Kabat, P., Verhoef, A., A system to measure surface fluxes of momentum, sensible heat, water vapour and carbon dioxide (1997) J. Hydrol., 188 (189), pp. 589-611; Nilsson, S., Schvidenko, A., Stolbovoi, V., Gluck, M., Jonas, M., Obersteiner, M., (2000) Full Carbon Account for Russia, , http://www.iiasa.ac.at/Publications/Documents/IR-00-02l.pdf, Interim Report IR-00-021, HASA, Laxenburg, Austria, (Available as); Panikov, N.S., Dedysh, S.N., Cold season CH4 and CO2 emission fron boreal peat bogs (West Siberia): Winter fluxes and thaw activation dynamics (2000) Global Biogeochem. Cycles, 14, pp. 1071-1080; Panikov, N.S., Glagolev, M.V., Kravchenko, I.K., Mastepanov, M.A., Kosych, N.P., Mironycheva-Tokareva, N.P., Naumov, A.V., Maxutov, S., Variability of methane emission from West-Siberian Wetlands as related to vegetation type (1997) Ecol. Chem., 6, pp. 59-67; Robertson, G.P., Paul, E.A., Harwood, R.R., Greenhouse gases in intensive agriculture: Contributions of individual gases to radiative forcing of the atmosphere (2000) Science, 289, pp. 1922-1925; Schulze, E.-D., Productivity of forest in the Eurosiberian boreal region and their potential to act as a carbon sink-a synthesis (1999) Global Change Biol., 5, pp. 703-722; Takeuchi, W., Tamura, M., Yasuoka, Y., Estimation of methane emission from West Siberian wetland by scaling technique between NOAA AVHRR and SPOT HRV (2003) Remote Sens. Environ., 85, pp. 21-29; Titlyanova, A.A., Bulavko, G.I., Kudryashova, S.Y., Naumov, A.V., Smirnov, V.V., Tanasienko, A.A., The reserves and losses of organic carbon in the soils of Siberia (1998) Eurasian Soil Sci., 31, pp. 45-53; Turunen, J., Tahvanainen, T., Tolonen, K., Pitkanen, A., Carbon accumulation in West Siberian mires, Russia (2001) Global Biogeochem. Cycles, 15, pp. 285-296; Valentini, R., Respiration as the main determinant of carbon balance in European forests (2000) Nature, 404, pp. 861-865; Valentini, R., Dore, S., Marchi, G., Mollicone, D., Panfyorov, M., Rebmann, C., Kolle, O., Schulze, E.D., Carbon and water exchange of two contrasting central Siberia landscape types: Regenerating forest and bog (2000) Func. Ecol., 14, pp. 87-96; Whiting, G.J., Chanton, J.P., Greenhouse gas balance of wetlands: Methane emission versus carbon sequestration (2001) Tellus, 53 B, pp. 521-528","Friborg, T.; Institute of Geography, Univ. of Copenhagen, Oester Voldgade 10, Copenhagen 1350K, Denmark; email: tfj@geogr.ku.dk",,,,,,,,00948276,,GPRLA,,"English","Geophys. Res. Lett.",Article,Scopus,2-s2.0-1642316430
